nd European—underline the international and transnational aspects of Ukrainian literature. The novel ends on a hopeful note even though by then the main characters have already died twice: they return with greater power each time. As the author’s last novel written originally in the Russian language, The Length of Days is a deeply Ukrainian work, set mostly in the composite Donbas city of Z—an uncanny foretelling of what this letter has come to symbolize since February 24, 2022, when Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMagic realism (Literature). 0aRusso-Ukrainian War, 2014-vFiction. 0aUkraine Conflict, 2014-vFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aDPR.  aDonbas.  aDonetsk People’s Republic.  aDonetsk.  aRussian aggression.  aRussian propaganda.  aUkraine.  aUkrainian literature.  adisplacement.  aexile.  ainvasion.  amigration.1 aForrester, Sibelan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShore, Marci, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107857910 cprintz978067429120140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674291232?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674291232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674291232/ori